04998nam a22006735i 9781478012702DE-B159720220424125308.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220424t20212021ncu    fo  d z      eng d  a2020029360  a9781478012702  a(DE-B1597)577367  a(OCoLC)1243310511  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ancucUS-NC00aHM1206 4aHM1206b.B455 2021 7aPHI0190002bisacsh04a302.232231 aBeller, Jonathan, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe World Computer :bDerivative Conditions of Racial Capitalism /cJonathan Beller. 1aDurham : bDuke University Press, c[2021] 4c©2021  a1 online resource (350 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aThought in the Act : 1800tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tAcknowledgments -- tI Computational Racial Capitalism -- tIntroduction: The Social Difference Engine and the World Computer -- t1 The Computational Unconscious: Technology as a Racial Formation -- tII The Computational Mode of Production -- t2 M–I– C– I′– M′: The Programmable Image of Photo-Capital -- t3 M–I– M′: Informatic Labor and Data- Visual Interruptions in Capital’s “Concise Style” -- tIII Derivative Conditions -- t4 Advertisarial Relations and Aesthetics of Survival -- t5 An Engine and a Camera -- t6 Derivative Living and Subaltern Futures: Film as Derivative, Cryptocurrency as Film -- tAppendix 1: The Derivative Machine: Life Cut, Bundled, and Sold— Notes on the Cinema -- tAppendix 2: The Derivative Image: Interview by Susana Nascimento Duarte -- tNotes -- tReferences -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn The World Computer Jonathan Beller forcefully demonstrates that the history of commodification generates information itself. Out of the omnipresent calculus imposed by commodification, information emerges historically as a new money form. Investigating its subsequent financialization of daily life and colonization of semiotics, Beller situates the development of myriad systems for quantifying the value of people, objects, and affects as endemic to racial capitalism and computation. Built on oppression and genocide, capital and its technical result as computation manifest as racial formations, as do the machines and software of social mediation that feed racial capitalism and run on social difference. Algorithms, derived from for-profit management strategies, conscript all forms of expression—language, image, music, communication—into the calculus of capital such that even protest may turn a profit. Computational media function for the purpose of extraction rather than ameliorating global crises, and financialize every expressive act, converting each utterance into a wager. Repairing this ecology of exploitation, Beller contends, requires decolonizing information and money, and the scripting of futures wagered by the cultural legacies and claims of those in struggle.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2022) 0aDigital mediaxSocial aspects. 0aMass mediaxSocial aspects. 0aRace in mass media. 7aPHILOSOPHY / Political.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDuke University Press Complete eBook-Package 2021z978311074331908iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2021 Englishz978311075400108iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2021z9783110753776oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Philosophy 2021 Englishz978311075415508iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Philosophy 2021z9783110753929oZDB-23-DPH40uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978147801270240uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781478012702423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781478012702/original  a978-3-11-07